Exhibit 99.1
 
 
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
 
 
 
 AnnTaylor Stores Corporation (NYSE:ANN) announced today that total net sales for the five-week period ended December 31, 2005 increased 11.6 percent to $267,695,000 over total net sales of $239,924,000 for the five-week period ended January 1, 2005. By division, net sales were $114,463,000 for Ann Taylor compared to $110,165,000 last year, and $128,811,000 for Ann Taylor LOFT compared to $107,436,000 last year.
New York, New York, January 5, 2006
 
Comparable store sales for the period increased 1.5 percent compared to a comparable store sales decrease of 1.5 percent for the same five-week period last year. By division, comparable store sales for fiscal December 2005 were up 2.3 percent for Ann Taylor compared to a 7.4 percent decrease last year, and up 1.6 percent for Ann Taylor LOFT compared to a 6.3 percent increase last year.
 
Kay Krill, President & Chief Executive Officer of Ann Taylor, stated, "During December, both divisions experienced positive comparable store sales in all regions despite mid to high single-digit declines in traffic. At Ann Taylor, given the strong momentum we experienced in November, sales were somewhat lower than expected. However, two categories that were particularly well received were sweaters and special occasion. LOFT performed in line with our expectations for the month, highlighted by strength in sweaters, separates, dresses and special occasion offerings. Based on our December and year-to-date results, we remain comfortable with our previous guidance of earnings per diluted share of $1.17, though we continue to carefully monitor the highly promotional retail environment."
 
The Company continued to carefully manage inventory, with total inventory levels at the end of December down approximately 19 percent on a per square foot basis compared to the same period last year. Inventory levels on a per square foot basis were down approximately 15 percent for both divisions.
